In a Jenkinsfile (Declarative Pipeline):

Type	How to access	Example
Environment variables	env.*	env.MY_ENV_VAR
Parameters (Pipeline parameters)	params.*	params.BRANCH_NAME
ğŸŒ Environment variables (env)

These come from:

Jenkins global environment

Agent machine OS env vars

environment {} block in Jenkinsfile

Example:

environment {
    MY_ENV_VAR = "HelloWorld"
}


Access in pipeline:

echo "Value = ${env.MY_ENV_VAR}"

ğŸ›ï¸ Parameters (params)

These are values passed by the user via Build With Parameters.

Example:

parameters {
    string(name: 'USERNAME', defaultValue: 'sumit')
    booleanParam(name: 'RUN_TESTS', defaultValue: true)
}


Access in pipeline:

echo "User = ${params.USERNAME}"
echo "Run tests? = ${params.RUN_TESTS}"

ğŸ”¥ Very simple memory rule
Prefix	Means
env.	Environment variable
params.	Parameter chosen by user

Example usage difference:

echo "Environment Workspace = ${env.WORKSPACE}"
echo "Selected branch = ${params.GIT_BRANCH}"

ğŸ§ª Quick real-life Jenkins example
pipeline {
    agent any

    parameters {
        string(name: 'BRANCH', defaultValue: 'main')
    }

    environment {
        URL = "https://google.com"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Show Values') {
            steps {
                echo "PARAM value = ${params.BRANCH}"
                echo "ENV value = ${env.URL}"
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸ§  Common mistakes to avoid

âŒ Wrong â€” missing prefix:

echo "${MY_ENV_VAR}"
echo "${BRANCH}"


âœ” Correct:

echo "${env.MY_ENV_VAR}"
echo "${params.BRANCH}"


âŒ Wrong â€” mixing up env and params

echo "${env.BRANCH}"  // BRANCH is a parameter, not env


âœ” Correct:

echo "${params.BRANCH}"

â­ Final takeaway

| env. | for environment variables |
| params. | for Jenkins pipeline parameters |

So your understanding is correct:

â€œglobal environment is accessed via env, and parameters via params.â€